This is actually what's on
the back of the handout,

00:34:57.830 --> 00:34:59.121
but you probably don't need it.

00:35:02.770 --> 00:35:03.960
There is a handout.

00:35:03.960 --> 00:35:06.260
Do you have it?

00:35:06.260 --> 00:35:10.272
So just take a minute to
think about, what could I do?

00:35:10.272 --> 00:35:11.980
What could I do now
that would strengthen

00:35:11.980 --> 00:35:14.460
the skill that
matters much to me?

00:35:14.460 --> 00:35:16.820
And what positive
impact would that

00:35:16.820 --> 00:35:20.810
have on the different parts?

00:35:20.810 --> 00:35:25.080
All right, so just take a
minute to think of an idea.

00:35:25.080 --> 00:35:26.902
It can be half formed.

00:35:26.902 --> 00:35:29.680
[CHATTER]

00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:33.870
All right, so here's
what I'd like you to do.

00:35:33.870 --> 00:35:36.020
Do you have an idea?

00:35:36.020 --> 00:35:36.770
AUDIENCE: Not yet.

00:35:36.770 --> 00:35:37.728
STEW FRIEDMAN: Not yet.

00:35:37.728 --> 00:35:39.810
You're still thinking?

00:35:39.810 --> 00:35:42.440
I want you to think with
somebody else, somebody

00:35:42.440 --> 00:35:44.720
preferably who you don't know.

00:35:44.720 --> 00:35:46.570
That would be better.

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:49.030
So what I'd like you to do
for the next five minutes,

00:35:49.030 --> 00:35:51.790
find a discussion partner,
preferably someone

00:35:51.790 --> 00:35:52.940
you do not know.

00:35:52.940 --> 00:35:56.599
It's better that
way and be more fun.

00:35:56.599 --> 00:35:58.890
Where you take a few minutes,
here's what I'm thinking.

00:35:58.890 --> 00:36:00.330
What do you think?

00:36:00.330 --> 00:36:02.490
And she does the same.

00:36:02.490 --> 00:36:04.263
Is this something
you're willing to do?

00:36:04.263 --> 00:36:05.030
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:36:05.030 --> 00:36:06.613
STEW FRIEDMAN: OK,
it's really simple.

00:36:06.613 --> 00:36:08.430
So you're coaching here, right?

00:36:08.430 --> 00:36:12.206
So all you have to do is, how
would practicing this skill

00:36:12.206 --> 00:36:13.580
create a greater
sense of harmony

00:36:13.580 --> 00:36:16.520
among the different parts
and improve all them?

00:36:16.520 --> 00:36:19.240
And what exactly would
you be doing here?

00:36:19.240 --> 00:36:22.790
And how would you know this
was improving your performance?

00:36:22.790 --> 00:36:25.990
So just ask those
questions, pay attention,

00:36:25.990 --> 00:36:29.280
give someone else the gift
of your caring attention

00:36:29.280 --> 00:36:30.859
for just a few minutes.

00:36:30.859 --> 00:36:35.350
[CHATTER]

00:36:49.830 --> 00:36:52.960
STEW FRIEDMAN: How can you
help each other going forward?

00:36:52.960 --> 00:36:54.520
I can tell you how.

00:36:54.520 --> 00:36:56.900
If you talk to each
other occasionally,

00:36:56.900 --> 00:37:01.250
maybe just text
or a quick hello.

00:37:01.250 --> 00:37:02.630
How is that idea going?

00:37:02.630 --> 00:37:03.740
Are you doing it?

00:37:03.740 --> 00:37:05.460
This is really important.

00:37:05.460 --> 00:37:07.544
And I know this from
literally decades

00:37:07.544 --> 00:37:08.960
of trying to do
this kind of work.

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:10.430
You cannot do it on your own.

00:37:10.430 --> 00:37:12.346
And if you have somebody
else who's interested

00:37:12.346 --> 00:37:14.606
and wants to help you and
learn by teaching you,

00:37:14.606 --> 00:37:17.500
you stay connected somehow
in a very light way.

00:37:17.500 --> 00:37:21.100
It doesn't have to be a
deep, long conversation.

00:37:21.100 --> 00:37:23.090
Just continue to pay attention.

00:37:23.090 --> 00:37:25.540
And I hope you
will continue that.

00:37:25.540 --> 00:37:29.902
Let me give you a really quick
overview of the three dozen

00:37:29.902 --> 00:37:31.860
exercises that are in
the back half of the book

00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:34.600
that you can choose from
to focus on these skills.

00:37:34.600 --> 00:37:38.100
So there's two exercises
that I've, again, curated

00:37:38.100 --> 00:37:42.220
from the literature on how
you create positive change

00:37:42.220 --> 00:37:43.640
for each one of the skills.

00:37:43.640 --> 00:37:45.670
So I'll just mention
a couple of them.

00:37:45.670 --> 00:37:46.660
And then we'll wrap up.

00:37:46.660 --> 00:37:50.260
So one of my favorites is
find the larger meaning

00:37:50.260 --> 00:37:52.715
in terms of trying to align
your actions with your values.

00:37:52.715 --> 00:37:55.090
And all that really asks you
to do-- it's pretty simple--

00:37:55.090 --> 00:37:57.467
is think about what's the
big purpose of what you're

00:37:57.467 --> 00:37:59.050
trying to do with
your work every day?

00:37:59.050 --> 00:38:00.675
A lot of people don't
think about that.

00:38:00.675 --> 00:38:04.490
And when you do, you
see a greater connection

00:38:04.490 --> 00:38:06.459
between what you're
doing, or you

00:38:06.459 --> 00:38:08.500
can find a greater connection
between what you're

00:38:08.500 --> 00:38:13.520
doing every day and what
is really important to you.

00:38:13.520 --> 00:38:17.690
Autobiography-- that's also
pretty straightforward.

00:38:17.690 --> 00:38:19.710
And if you want to
get good at conveying

00:38:19.710 --> 00:38:21.924
your values through stories,
which other people want

00:38:21.924 --> 00:38:23.840
to hear from you, because
they want to see you

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:26.230
as a human being just
like them, someone who

00:38:26.230 --> 00:38:29.470
has struggled to try to achieve
something that matters and has

00:38:29.470 --> 00:38:32.780
faced adversity and
somehow surmounted it,

00:38:32.780 --> 00:38:36.310
you reflect on the two or
three or four critical episodes

00:38:36.310 --> 00:38:39.880
of your life history that
have shaped who you are.

00:38:39.880 --> 00:38:41.940
And then figure out a
way to convey those,

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:45.250
if you're willing, to people who
would be interested in hearing

00:38:45.250 --> 00:38:48.800
about them as a way
of conveying, again,

00:38:48.800 --> 00:38:50.260
what matters most to you.

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:53.900
Time travel is another
cool thing to do.

00:38:53.900 --> 00:38:55.650
It's 15 years from now.

00:38:55.650 --> 00:38:57.010
Describe a day in the life.

00:38:57.010 --> 00:38:59.206
What happens?

00:38:59.206 --> 00:39:00.850
Who are you with
when you wake up?

00:39:00.850 --> 00:39:01.910
What are you doing?

00:39:01.910 --> 00:39:03.870
What impact are you
having on the world?

00:39:03.870 --> 00:39:06.540
So those are some
simple exercises

00:39:06.540 --> 00:39:11.380
to do to help you to get better
at acting with authenticity

00:39:11.380 --> 00:39:14.060
by clarifying what
matters most to you.

00:39:14.060 --> 00:39:16.230
For being whole, a
couple of exercises

00:39:16.230 --> 00:39:17.967
that you might want to try.

00:39:17.967 --> 00:39:19.550
We heard something
just like this now,

00:39:19.550 --> 00:39:22.070
the Segment and Merge exercise.

00:39:22.070 --> 00:39:25.650
So here what you
do is take some way

00:39:25.650 --> 00:39:28.830
in which the two parts of your
life, or three or four of them,

00:39:28.830 --> 00:39:29.550
intersect.

00:39:29.550 --> 00:39:32.240
And try segmenting them.

00:39:32.240 --> 00:39:33.990
And that's kind of
what you just did here.

00:39:33.990 --> 00:39:36.630
Bounding time and place
for just one thing,

00:39:36.630 --> 00:39:38.430
and it could be just
for five minutes,

00:39:38.430 --> 00:39:41.740
or it could be for a day,
or it could be for week.

00:39:41.740 --> 00:39:46.380
But try segmenting in a way
that you haven't before so

00:39:46.380 --> 00:39:50.740
that you can bring total
focus to one person or thing.

00:39:50.740 --> 00:39:52.410
See what happens.

00:39:52.410 --> 00:39:54.220
And then try the opposite.

00:39:54.220 --> 00:39:56.720
Try bringing together
two ports your life

00:39:56.720 --> 00:39:59.040
that normally would
be very separated.

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:00.570
And what happens there?

00:40:00.570 --> 00:40:02.590
And what you discover
by consciously

00:40:02.590 --> 00:40:05.490
and deliberately experimenting
with segmenting and merging

00:40:05.490 --> 00:40:09.190
is how to be smarter about
creating those boundaries.

00:40:09.190 --> 00:40:11.500
It really just take stepping
back, experimenting,

00:40:11.500 --> 00:40:14.210
and seeing what happens,
and then learning from that.

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:19.520
So those are some ideas
about being whole.

00:40:19.520 --> 00:40:21.940
Now, exercises for
practicing some

00:40:21.940 --> 00:40:24.400
of the skills of
being innovative--

00:40:24.400 --> 00:40:26.820
I'll just mention two,
and then we'll wrap up.

00:40:26.820 --> 00:40:30.582
Crowdsourcing solution-- so most
people in this room I suspect

00:40:30.582 --> 00:40:31.790
are probably pretty creative.

00:40:31.790 --> 00:40:32.990
But sometimes you get stuck.

00:40:32.990 --> 00:40:36.789
And you see a dilemma, and you
just can't find a solution.

00:40:36.789 --> 00:40:38.830
A really simple way to do
this-- and you probably

00:40:38.830 --> 00:40:41.550
do this in your work life pretty
regularly-- bring together

00:40:41.550 --> 00:40:44.420
a couple of people who
you trust and you're

00:40:44.420 --> 00:40:47.930
willing to talk about
opportunities for alternatives.

00:40:47.930 --> 00:40:49.700
And generate creative
solutions with them.

00:40:49.700 --> 00:40:52.590
So you crowdsource
solutions to problems

00:40:52.590 --> 00:40:55.290
that you're facing in the
different parts of your life.

00:40:55.290 --> 00:40:59.070
And finally, challenging
your beliefs-- research

00:40:59.070 --> 00:41:04.150
on behavioral therapy
for depression,

00:41:04.150 --> 00:41:07.790
cognitive behavioral therapy,
is quite profound insights

00:41:07.790 --> 00:41:12.359
from that literature, which show
that a lot of what holds people

00:41:12.359 --> 00:41:14.900
back from trying something new
that's going to make them feel

00:41:14.900 --> 00:41:16.608
a greater sense of
control in their lives

00:41:16.608 --> 00:41:19.160
is their beliefs about
what might happen

00:41:19.160 --> 00:41:21.240
if they did try something new.

00:41:21.240 --> 00:41:23.780
And if you challenge
those, and the exercise

00:41:23.780 --> 00:41:25.270
that I describe
in the book helps

00:41:25.270 --> 00:41:28.280
you to just in a simple
way look at the beliefs

00:41:28.280 --> 00:41:30.810
that you have about a
certain course of action.

00:41:30.810 --> 00:41:34.740
It actually minimizes your
own resistance and your fear.

00:41:34.740 --> 00:41:39.280
There's lots more, but we're
reaching the end of the hour.

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:43.640
I hope that these ideas
have sparked your thinking

00:41:43.640 --> 00:41:49.420
about what you can do to build
the capacity to bring together

00:41:49.420 --> 00:41:51.150
the different
parts of your life.

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:53.570
Let me just ask
you really quickly,

00:41:53.570 --> 00:41:55.550
what do you take
away from what we've

00:41:55.550 --> 00:41:56.510
been talking about
here, what I've

00:41:56.510 --> 00:41:58.009
been saying for the
last hour or so?

00:41:58.009 --> 00:42:00.280
What's the big idea for you?

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:01.544
AUDIENCE: Action.

00:42:01.544 --> 00:42:02.460
STEW FRIEDMAN: Action.

00:42:02.460 --> 00:42:04.110
That's it.

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:05.980
Just do something, yes.

00:42:05.980 --> 00:42:08.880
So I begin the second
part of the book,

00:42:08.880 --> 00:42:11.850
after telling the stories, with,
when you read these stories,

00:42:11.850 --> 00:42:15.040
you'll see the thing that comes
through is just this idea.

00:42:15.040 --> 00:42:16.770
These people don't sit still.

00:42:16.770 --> 00:42:19.070
They're moving,
moving all the time

00:42:19.070 --> 00:42:21.364
and then reflecting
on what it is

00:42:21.364 --> 00:42:23.030
that they're learning
from their action.

00:42:23.030 --> 00:42:24.154
What else do you take away?

00:42:24.154 --> 00:42:25.250
AUDIENCE: Small changes.

00:42:25.250 --> 00:42:27.249
STEW FRIEDMAN: Small
changes towards a big idea.

00:42:27.249 --> 00:42:29.730
It's something we
all know intuitively.

00:42:29.730 --> 00:42:32.300
And it's within
everyone's grasp.

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:35.230
And that's the beauty of small.

00:42:35.230 --> 00:42:37.720
You make it small enough
so that other people aren't

00:42:37.720 --> 00:42:41.140
terrified by what you're trying,
and they see that, in fact,

00:42:41.140 --> 00:42:44.840
what you're trying to do is good
for them, too, assuming it is,

00:42:44.840 --> 00:42:47.340
and of course, that's part of
what you think about here when

00:42:47.340 --> 00:42:49.380
you take the four-way view.

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:49.920
What else?

00:42:49.920 --> 00:42:51.690
Let's get one more.

00:42:51.690 --> 00:42:52.219
Yeah?

00:42:52.219 --> 00:42:54.010
AUDIENCE: There's no
such thing as balance.

00:42:54.010 --> 00:42:56.010
STEW FRIEDMAN: There's
no such thing as balance.

00:42:56.010 --> 00:42:58.120
All right, that's
a fitting-- I mean,

00:42:58.120 --> 00:43:01.850
you can talk about balance,
but it's misguided.

00:43:01.850 --> 00:43:05.735
The metaphor I prefer
is the jazz quartet.

00:43:05.735 --> 00:43:07.760
So you've got these
four instruments, right?

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:09.440
And they're
improvising on a theme

00:43:09.440 --> 00:43:11.007
over the course of
your whole life.

00:43:11.007 --> 00:43:12.590
You're trying to
make beautiful music.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:16.410
But sometimes you only
hear the trumpet, right?

00:43:16.410 --> 00:43:18.880
Sometimes maybe it's only
family or it's only work.

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:22.200
Sometimes you just hear
the bass and the drums.

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:24.380
It doesn't have to all
be at the same amplitude

00:43:24.380 --> 00:43:28.110
at the same time, thinking
instead about harmony

00:43:28.110 --> 00:43:30.400
over the long haul.

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:31.960
That's what these
folks have done.

00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:36.080
They also prove
that achievement,

00:43:36.080 --> 00:43:38.350
significant achievement
in the world,

00:43:38.350 --> 00:43:43.530
comes from taking action, taking
compassionate action that's

00:43:43.530 --> 00:43:45.990
designed to take whatever
is unique about you,

00:43:45.990 --> 00:43:47.980
your passions, your
skills, your talents,

00:43:47.980 --> 00:43:49.990
and bringing them to
bear in a positive way

00:43:49.990 --> 00:43:51.400
on the world around you.

00:43:51.400 --> 00:43:53.150
That's what each of
these people has done.

00:43:53.150 --> 00:43:54.525
And if you think
about the people

00:43:54.525 --> 00:43:57.190
you admire who have had
lives of significance,

00:43:57.190 --> 00:44:00.270
I'm pretty sure they will
have done the same thing.

00:44:00.270 --> 00:44:04.760
So the paradox of the title is
that leading the life you want

00:44:04.760 --> 00:44:10.320
requires striving all the time
to be helping other people.

00:44:10.320 --> 00:44:13.790
That's what's liberating is the
idea of taking what you have

00:44:13.790 --> 00:44:15.420
and bringing it to the world.

00:44:15.420 --> 00:44:20.700
And that finally, accomplishment
in one's career or public life

00:44:20.700 --> 00:44:23.630
comes not so much at the
expense of the other parts,

00:44:23.630 --> 00:44:26.440
but rather because
of the commitments

00:44:26.440 --> 00:44:29.540
that you have to the
different parts of your life.

00:44:29.540 --> 00:44:33.820
And you can develop these
skills if you focus on doing so.

00:44:33.820 --> 00:44:35.770
And I hope that you'll
continue to do that.

00:44:35.770 --> 00:44:38.370
So thanks for joining us
today and for your attention.

00:44:38.370 --> 00:44:40.440
And thanks again,
Ashley, for inviting me.

00:44:40.440 --> 00:44:44.390
[APPLAUSE]

